Bank Churn Prediction¶

Objective¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not.

Context¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Description¶

Based on the problem statement, the description of the columns are

RowNumber       Row number for the entry
CustomerId      Unique customer ID
Surname         Surname of the customer
CreditScore     Credit Score of the customer
Geography       Geographical location of the customer
Gender          Gender of the customer
Age             Age of the customer
Tenure          Tenure of the customer with this bank
Balance         Customer balance with the bank
NumOfProducts   Number of products from the bank, that the customer uses
HasCrCard       Indicates whether the customer has a credit card
IsActiveMember  Indicates if the cutomer is an active member of the bank
EstimatedSalary Estimated salary of the customer
Exited          Indicates if the customer exited the bank
Observation¶
  • Based on the description, the datatypes matches

Distribution¶

In [13]:
num_plots = len(categorical_columns)
total_cols = 3
total_rows = 2
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=total_rows, ncols=total_cols, figsize=(20, 10))
for i, var in enumerate(categorical_columns):
    row = i//total_cols
    pos = i % total_cols
    ax = sns.countplot(bank_churn_df[var], edgecolor="black", ax=axs[row][pos])
    total = len(bank_churn_df[var])
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.0f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + 0.4
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x,y), size = 12, ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
    ax.set_title("Distribution of {0}".format(var), pad=15)
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)
fig.tight_layout(pad=3.5)
plt.show();
Observation¶
  • Geography - Majority of customers(50%) are from France, and the remaining equally distributed from Spain and Germany
  • Gender - Majority of customers(55%) are Male. Female customers are close second at 45%
  • HasCrCard - Majority of customers(71%) have a credit card.
  • IsActiveMember - 52% of customers are active, wheareas 48% are not
  • Tenure - Tenure of the customers are equally distributed between 1-9 years. Whereas 4% of customers have no tenure and 5% of customer have tenure of 10 years.
  • NumOfProducts - Majority of customers(51%) use only 1 product from the bank and closely 46% of customers use 2 products from the bank.

Distribution with Target¶

In [14]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=total_rows, ncols=total_cols, figsize=(20, 10))
for i, var in enumerate(categorical_columns):
    row = i//total_cols
    pos = i % total_cols
    ax = sns.countplot(x=var, hue="Exited", data=bank_churn_df, edgecolor="black", ax=axs[row][pos])
    total = len(bank_churn_df[var])
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.0f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
        x = p.get_x() + 0.2
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x,y), size = 12, ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
    ax.set_title("Distribution of {0} with Exited".format(var), pad=15)
    ax.set_xticklabels(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)
# axs[1,2].set_axis_off()
fig.tight_layout(pad=4.5)
plt.show();
Observation¶
  • Georgraphy - Customers who exited, are equally distributed in France and Germany at 8%. Spain comes seconds at 4%
  • Gender - Though the distribution shows there are more Male customers as compared to Female customers, of those who exited, we see the majority are Female at 11%
  • HasCrCard - 14% of customers with credit card, exited. This could be a contributing factor.
  • IsActiveMember - Only 7% of active customers exited, whereas 13% of inactive customers exited. This could be a contributing factor.
  • Tenure - Between 1-9 years, 2% of customers exited and this is equally distributed. Whereas only 1% of customers with tenure of 10 exited.
  • NumOfProducts - 14% of customers using 1 product exited, whereas customers with 2 products exited only 3%. This could also mean, customers using more products have a tie in with the bank and quit less frequently

Correlation Matrix¶

In [17]:
# Graphical representation of the correlation
correlation = bank_churn_df.corr()

# Generate a custom diverging colormap
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 10, as_cmap=True)

fig_corr, axes_corr = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1, figsize=(12,10))

# Hide the upper half of the matrix - So that we see the values only once
mask = np.zeros_like(correlation)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask, 1)] = True
sns.heatmap(correlation, ax=axes_corr,  linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={"shrink": .5}, cmap=cmap, vmin=-1, annot=True, fmt=".2f", mask=mask)
fig_corr.suptitle("Correlation Matrix", fontsize=14)
plt.yticks(fontsize=10, va="center")
fig_corr.tight_layout(pad=4.5)
plt.show();
Observation¶
  • We dont observe any high correlation on either direction among the columns (for removal) or with the target column (Exited).
  • Balance has a small negative correlation with NumOfProducts, but doesnt seem high enough to be significant.
  • Age seems to have a small postive correlation with Exited. But not very significant

ANN¶

Important Metric¶

  • TP (True Positive) - Predict that the customer will exit, and they exited
  • FP (False Positive) - Predict that the customer will exit, but they did not
  • FN (False Negative) - Predict that the customer will not exit, but they exited
  • TN (True Negative) - Predict that the customer will not exit and they did not

  • Based on this, we can see that the bank would like to target those customers who actually exited. Its important for the bank to know that they customer will exit. Predicting a customer will not exit, but if they did exit, that is bad for the bank. So the bank would like to have a lower FN, which means, we need to reduce the Recall which becomes the important metric to track.

Baseline Metrics¶

In [37]:
def calculate_metrics(actual, predicted):
    accuracy = accuracy_score(actual, predicted)
    precision = precision_score(actual, predicted)
    recall = recall_score(actual, predicted)
    f1 = f1_score(actual, predicted)
    auc = roc_auc_score(actual, predicted)
    return (accuracy, precision, recall, f1, auc)
In [38]:
def plot_loss(history):
    metrics =  ['loss']
    for n, metric in enumerate(metrics):
        fig_conf, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, figsize=(20,5))
        name = metric.replace("_"," ").capitalize()
        axs[1].plot(history.epoch,  history.history[metric], color=colors[0], label='Train')
        axs[1].plot(history.epoch, history.history['val_'+metric], color=colors[0], linestyle="--", label='Val')
        axs[1].set_xlabel('Epoch')
        axs[1].set_ylabel(name)
        axs[1].legend()
        axs[0].set_axis_off()
        axs[2].set_axis_off()
        fig_conf.tight_layout(pad=3.5)
        plt.show();

In [41]:
def create_confusion_matrix(axs, row, pos, description, actual, predicted, loss, accuracy, precision, recall, f1, auc):
    if axs.ndim > 1:
        axis_heat_map = axs[row][pos]
    else:
        axis_heat_map = axs[pos]

    labels = ["TN","FP","FN","TP"]
    cf = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    group_labels = ["{}\n\n".format(value) for value in labels]
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])
    
    stats_text = "\n\nLoss = {:0.3f}\nAccuracy = {:0.3f}\nPrecision = {:0.3f}\nRecall = {:0.3f}\nF1 = {:0.3f}\nAUC = {:0.3f}\n".format(loss, accuracy, precision, recall, f1, auc)
    
    heatmap = sns.heatmap(cf, annot=box_labels, annot_kws={"size": 14}, linewidths=0.5, linecolor='w', fmt="", cmap="Oranges", cbar=False, xticklabels="auto", yticklabels="auto", ax=axis_heat_map, square=True)
    axis_heat_map.set_title(description, fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_ylabel("Actual", fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_xlabel("Predicted" + stats_text, fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_xticklabels(axis_heat_map.get_xticklabels(), rotation = 45, fontsize = 10)
    axis_heat_map.set_yticklabels(axis_heat_map.get_yticklabels(), rotation = 25, fontsize = 10)
    
    return_list = [value for value in cf.flatten()]
    return return_list

Improvement 2 - Oversampling the minority class¶

This is a related approach, wherein, to handle the class imbalance, we will oversample the minority class.

In [51]:
# Collect list of positive and negative features and labels
pos_features = train_features[bool_train_labels]
neg_features = train_features[~bool_train_labels]

pos_labels = train_labels[bool_train_labels]
neg_labels = train_labels[~bool_train_labels]
In [52]:
# Randomly choose ids from the positive features (replicate), as much as the number of negative features
ids = np.arange(len(pos_features))
choices = np.random.choice(ids, len(neg_features))

# For the randmom replicated id, get the features and label (set of rows which are duplicates from existing rows)
res_pos_features = pos_features[choices]
res_pos_labels = pos_labels[choices]

res_pos_features.shape
Out[52]:
(5095, 13)
In [53]:
# Concatenate the replicated rows with negative features and labels
resampled_features = np.concatenate([res_pos_features, neg_features], axis=0)
resampled_labels = np.concatenate([res_pos_labels, neg_labels], axis=0)

order = np.arange(len(resampled_labels))
np.random.shuffle(order)
resampled_features = resampled_features[order]
resampled_labels = resampled_labels[order]

resampled_features.shape

Improvement 4 - Different Learning Rates and Optimizers¶

In [66]:
def create_improvement_model(learning_rate, optimizer):
    weighted_improvement_model = Sequential()

    weighted_improvement_model.add(Dense(64, input_shape = (train_features.shape[-1],), activation = 'relu'))
    weighted_improvement_model.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid')) 

    if optimizer == "Adagrad":
        opt = keras.optimizers.Adagrad(lr = learning_rate)
    elif optimizer == "Adam":
        opt = keras.optimizers.Adam(lr = learning_rate)
    elif optimizer == "Adamax":
        opt = keras.optimizers.Adamax(lr = learning_rate)
    elif optimizer == "Nadam":
        opt = keras.optimizers.Nadam(lr = learning_rate)
    elif optimizer == "RMSprop":
        opt = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr = learning_rate)
    elif optimizer == "SGD":
        opt = keras.optimizers.SGD(lr = learning_rate)

    weighted_improvement_model.compile(optimizer = opt, loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics=METRICS)
    return weighted_improvement_model

  • If the bank feels that reaching out to customer who dont intend to exit, is not ok, then the bank should choose a model that has good Precision and the table above should give a good idea of the performance of the models
  • Also since there is an imbalance in the classes of the data, it made the problem difficult. We can try other methods to address this, like:
    • SMOTE
    • Providing proper initial bias to Tensorflow (as discussed in https://www.tensorflow.org/tutorials/structured_data/imbalanced_data#optional_set_the_correct_initial_bias)
